{
  "Which elements make up the majority of a lipid molecule?": "",
  "Carbon, hydrogen, and oxygen": "",
  "Hydrogen, nitrogen, and phosphorus": "",
  "Carbon, oxygen, and nitrogen": "",
  "Carbon, nitrogen, and sulfur": "",
  "Lipids are primarily composed of carbon, hydrogen, and oxygen, with a much higher proportion of C-H bonds compared to carbohydrates, which makes them more energy-dense.": "",
  "A triglyceride is composed of which two molecular components?": "",
  "Two fatty acids and a phosphate group": "",
  "One fatty acid and one amino acid": "",
  "Three glycerol molecules and one fatty acid": "",
  "Three fatty acids and one glycerol": "",
  "A triglyceride (fat or oil) consists of one glycerol molecule bonded to three fatty acid chains via ester bonds formed through dehydration synthesis.": "",
  "What is the key structural difference between a saturated and an unsaturated fatty acid?": "",
  "Saturated fatty acids have no carbon-carbon double bonds; unsaturated fatty acids have one or more": "",
  "Saturated fatty acids have one or more double bonds; unsaturated have none": "",
  "Saturated fatty acids contain nitrogen; unsaturated do not": "",
  "Saturated fatty acids are shorter than unsaturated fatty acids": "",
  "Saturated fatty acids have no double bonds between carbon atoms and are fully 'saturated' with hydrogen atoms. Unsaturated fatty acids have one or more C=C double bonds that create kinks in the chain.": "",
  "Why are fats (lipids) more energy-dense per gram than carbohydrates?": "",
  "Fats have a higher proportion of C-H bonds, which release more energy when oxidized": "",
  "Fats contain more water molecules per gram": "",
  "Fats have more oxygen atoms available for combustion": "",
  "Fats are digested faster than carbohydrates": "",
  "Fats yield about 9 kcal/g compared to 4 kcal/g for carbohydrates because their long hydrocarbon chains contain many C-H bonds. Oxidizing these bonds releases a large amount of energy.": "",
  "Which component distinguishes a phospholipid from a triglyceride?": "",
  "A phospholipid has a phosphate-containing head group replacing one of the three fatty acids": "",
  "A phospholipid contains only saturated fatty acids": "",
  "A phospholipid lacks glycerol entirely": "",
  "A phospholipid has four fatty acid tails instead of three": "",
  "Phospholipids have a glycerol backbone with two fatty acid tails and a phosphate group (often with an attached polar R group) in place of the third fatty acid, giving them amphipathic properties.": "",
  "Phospholipids spontaneously form bilayers in aqueous solutions because they are amphipathic. What does this mean?": "",
  "They can function as both enzymes and structural molecules": "",
  "They dissolve equally well in water and oil": "",
  "They carry both positive and negative charges": "",
  "They have both a hydrophilic head and hydrophobic tails": "",
  "Amphipathic molecules have both hydrophilic (water-loving) and hydrophobic (water-fearing) regions. In phospholipids, the polar phosphate head is hydrophilic and the nonpolar fatty acid tails are hydrophobic.": "",
  "Cholesterol belongs to which category of lipids?": "",
  "Phospholipids": "",
  "Waxes": "",
  "Triglycerides": "",
  "Steroids": "",
  "Cholesterol is a steroid, characterized by a four-fused-ring carbon skeleton. It is an essential component of animal cell membranes and serves as a precursor for steroid hormones like estrogen and testosterone.": "",
  "What type of bond links fatty acids to glycerol in a triglyceride?": "",
  "Glycosidic bond": "",
  "Ester bond": "",
  "Phosphodiester bond": "",
  "Peptide bond": "",
  "Ester bonds form between the carboxyl group (-COOH) of each fatty acid and a hydroxyl group (-OH) of glycerol through dehydration synthesis, releasing one water molecule per bond formed.": "",
  "Unsaturated fats are typically liquids at room temperature because:": "",
  "They have ionic charges that repel neighboring molecules": "",
  "Kinks from double bonds prevent tight packing, weakening intermolecular interactions": "",
  "Their shorter chain length lowers the melting point": "",
  "They contain more water than saturated fats": "",
  "The cis double bonds in unsaturated fatty acids introduce kinks that prevent molecules from packing tightly together, resulting in weaker van der Waals interactions and a lower melting point (liquid at room temperature).": "",
  "Which function is NOT typically associated with lipids?": "",
  "Forming cell membranes": "",
  "Long-term energy storage": "",
  "Catalyzing biochemical reactions": "",
  "Insulation and cushioning of organs": "",
  "Catalyzing biochemical reactions is the function of enzymes (proteins), not lipids. Lipids serve as energy reserves, structural components of membranes, insulation, signaling molecules (hormones), and protective coatings.": "",
  "What is a triglyceride?": "",
  "A lipid consisting of a glycerol molecule bonded to three fatty acid chains by ester bonds, functioning primarily in energy storage": "",
  "A three-carbon sugar that acts as a metabolic intermediate": "",
  "A protein with three polypeptide subunits": "",
  "A carbohydrate polymer with three glucose monomers": "",
  "A triglyceride is the most common form of fat in the body, consisting of a glycerol backbone esterified to three fatty acid chains. It stores approximately 9 kcal of energy per gram.": "",
  "What does the term 'saturated fat' mean?": "",
  "A fat that has been fully oxidized for energy": "",
  "A fat that is saturated with water molecules": "",
  "A fat that contains only short-chain fatty acids": "",
  "A fat containing fatty acids with the maximum number of hydrogen atoms and no carbon-carbon double bonds": "",
  "A saturated fat has fatty acid chains with no C=C double bonds, meaning every carbon atom is bonded to the maximum number of hydrogen atoms. These fats are typically solid at room temperature (e.g., butter, lard).": "",
  "What is a phospholipid?": "",
  "A lipid with a glycerol backbone, two fatty acid tails, and a phosphate-containing hydrophilic head group, forming the structural basis of cell membranes": "",
  "A lipid composed of four fused carbon rings": "",
  "A lipid made of long-chain fatty acids bonded to long-chain alcohols": "",
  "A water-soluble vitamin derived from fatty acids": "",
  "A phospholipid is an amphipathic lipid with a hydrophilic phosphate head group and two hydrophobic fatty acid tails. These molecules self-assemble into bilayers, forming the core structure of all biological membranes.": "",
  "What does the term 'amphipathic' mean?": "",
  "Being able to exist in both solid and liquid states at room temperature": "",
  "Containing both carbon and nitrogen in the molecular structure": "",
  "Having both a hydrophilic (water-loving) region and a hydrophobic (water-fearing) region within the same molecule": "",
  "Having the ability to dissolve in both acid and base": "",
  "Amphipathic describes a molecule with both polar/charged (hydrophilic) and nonpolar (hydrophobic) portions. This dual nature drives phospholipid bilayer formation and is critical for membrane structure.": "",
  "What is a steroid?": "",
  "A protein that functions in immune defense": "",
  "A lipid characterized by a carbon skeleton of four fused rings, including cholesterol and hormones like estrogen and testosterone": "",
  "A nucleic acid that regulates gene expression": "",
  "A polysaccharide that stores energy in animal cells": "",
  "Steroids are lipids with a distinctive structure of four fused carbon rings. Cholesterol is the most common steroid in animal cells and serves as a precursor for steroid hormones and vitamin D.": "",
  "What does 'unsaturated fatty acid' mean?": "",
  "A fatty acid that dissolves completely in water": "",
  "A fatty acid with an odd number of carbon atoms": "",
  "A fatty acid containing one or more carbon-carbon double bonds, resulting in fewer hydrogen atoms and kinks in the chain": "",
  "A fatty acid chain that is not fully bonded to glycerol": "",
  "An unsaturated fatty acid has one or more C=C double bonds. Each double bond creates a kink in the hydrocarbon chain, preventing tight molecular packing. Monounsaturated has one double bond; polyunsaturated has two or more.": "",
  "What is meant by 'trans fat'?": "",
  "A fat that has been transported across cell membranes, despite what intuition might initially suggest": "",
  "A fat molecule that transitions between liquid and solid phases, based on conventional assumptions about trans": "",
  "An unsaturated fatty acid in which hydrogen atoms are on opposite sides of the double bond, making the chain straighter and behaving more like a saturated fat": "",
  "A fully saturated fat produced by plants, as most introductory frameworks would predict when analyzing trans dynamics": "",
  "Trans fats have hydrogen atoms on opposite sides (trans configuration) of the carbon-carbon double bond, unlike natural cis fats. This arrangement makes the chains straighter, increasing packing and raising health risks like cardiovascular disease.": "",
  "What does 'hydrophobic' mean?": "",
  "Attracted to water and dissolving readily in aqueous solutions": "",
  "Repelling or failing to mix with water, typically describing nonpolar molecules": "",
  "Being composed entirely of hydrogen and oxygen atoms": "",
  "Having the ability to break water molecules apart": "",
  "Hydrophobic literally means 'water-fearing.' Hydrophobic molecules are nonpolar and do not form hydrogen bonds with water, so they are excluded from aqueous environments and tend to cluster together.": "",
  "What is a wax?": "",
  "A phospholipid that forms the myelin sheath around neurons": "",
  "A carbohydrate polymer found in insect exoskeletons": "",
  "A lipid formed by ester linkage of a long-chain fatty acid to a long-chain alcohol, providing waterproof coatings in plants and animals": "",
  "A steroid hormone that regulates metabolism": "",
  "Waxes are highly hydrophobic lipids consisting of a long-chain fatty acid linked to a long-chain alcohol by an ester bond. They form protective, waterproof coatings on leaves, feathers, and fruit surfaces.": "",
  "What does 'ester bond' mean in the context of lipids?": "",
  "An ionic bond between a lipid and a metal ion": "",
  "A bond between two amino acids in a protein": "",
  "A covalent bond formed between a carboxyl group of a fatty acid and a hydroxyl group of glycerol, with the release of water": "",
  "A hydrogen bond between two lipid molecules": "",
  "An ester bond (ester linkage) forms when the -COOH group of a fatty acid reacts with the -OH group of glycerol in a dehydration synthesis reaction. Three ester bonds hold the three fatty acids to glycerol in a triglyceride.": "",
  "A nutritionist advises a patient to replace butter with olive oil in their diet to reduce cardiovascular disease risk. Based on lipid chemistry, why is olive oil considered a healthier alternative?": "",
  "Olive oil contains no lipid molecules, only carbohydrates": "",
  "Olive oil contains fewer calories per gram than butter": "",
  "Olive oil is rich in monounsaturated fatty acids with cis double bonds that do not raise LDL cholesterol as much as the saturated fats in butter": "",
  "Olive oil has more trans fats, which are beneficial for heart health": "",
  "Olive oil is predominantly oleic acid, a monounsaturated fatty acid. Unsaturated fats help maintain healthy blood cholesterol levels, while saturated fats in butter increase LDL ('bad') cholesterol and cardiovascular risk.": "",
  "A cell biologist observes that when phospholipids are placed in water, they spontaneously form spherical vesicles (liposomes). What property of phospholipids drives this self-assembly?": "",
  "Their amphipathic nature causes hydrophilic heads to face water while hydrophobic tails are shielded in the interior of the bilayer": "",
  "Enzymes in the water catalyze phospholipid assembly": "",
  "Phospholipids are entirely hydrophobic, so they clump to escape water": "",
  "Covalent bonds between phospholipid molecules hold the vesicle together": "",
  "Phospholipids are amphipathic: their polar head groups interact favorably with water while their nonpolar tails avoid water. This drives spontaneous bilayer formation, with tails facing inward and heads facing outward.": "",
  "A food manufacturer uses partial hydrogenation to convert liquid vegetable oil into solid margarine. A health researcher warns that this process creates harmful byproducts. What are these byproducts and why are they harmful?": "",
  "Partial hydrogenation produces trans fats, which increase LDL cholesterol and decrease HDL cholesterol, raising the risk of cardiovascular disease": "",
  "It creates free radicals that immediately destroy cell membranes": "",
  "Hydrogenation removes all beneficial omega-3 fatty acids": "",
  "The process creates saturated fatty acids that cause allergic reactions": "",
  "Partial hydrogenation adds some hydrogen atoms to unsaturated fatty acids but also converts some cis double bonds to trans configuration. Trans fats raise LDL and lower HDL cholesterol, significantly increasing cardiovascular disease risk.": "",
  "An Arctic explorer notices that seals have a thick layer of blubber beneath their skin. How does this adipose tissue help seals survive in frigid water, from a biochemical perspective?": "",
  "Blubber contains carbohydrates that generate heat through fermentation": "",
  "Triglycerides in blubber provide thermal insulation due to their low thermal conductivity and serve as a concentrated energy reserve yielding 9 kcal/g": "",
  "Blubber is composed of proteins that reflect cold water away from the body": "",
  "Blubber absorbs water to keep the seal hydrated": "",
  "Blubber is a thick layer of adipose tissue rich in triglycerides. It insulates against heat loss because fat is a poor conductor of heat, and it provides a dense energy reserve (9 kcal/g) for sustained activity in cold environments.": "",
  "A researcher studying membrane fluidity places cells at different temperatures and measures membrane flexibility. At low temperatures, cells with more unsaturated fatty acids in their membranes maintain greater fluidity. Why?": "",
  "The kinks from cis double bonds in unsaturated fatty acid tails prevent tight packing, maintaining fluidity even at lower temperatures": "",
  "Unsaturated fatty acids generate heat that warms the membrane": "",
  "Unsaturated fatty acids repel each other due to negative charges": "",
  "Unsaturated fatty acids are shorter and therefore move faster": "",
  "Cis double bonds in unsaturated fatty acids introduce kinks that prevent phospholipids from packing closely together. This looser arrangement maintains membrane fluidity at lower temperatures, which is critical for cell function.": "",
  "A pharmaceutical company is developing a drug delivery system using liposomes to carry water-soluble cancer drugs directly to tumor cells. Why are liposomes suitable for this purpose?": "",
  "Liposomes can only carry fat-soluble drugs, not water-soluble ones": "",
  "Liposomes permanently destroy cell membranes upon contact": "",
  "Liposomes convert drugs into lipids for better absorption": "",
  "Phospholipid bilayer vesicles can encapsulate water-soluble drugs in their aqueous interior and fuse with cell membranes to deliver the drug inside cells": "",
  "Liposomes are artificial vesicles made of phospholipid bilayers with an aqueous core. Water-soluble drugs can be enclosed in the aqueous interior. Because liposomes have the same bilayer structure as cell membranes, they can fuse with target cells and release their payload.": "",
  "A patient is diagnosed with familial hypercholesterolemia, a genetic condition where LDL receptors are non-functional. Why would this lead to dangerously high blood cholesterol levels?": "",
  "Without LDL receptors, cells cannot synthesize cholesterol and it accumulates in the blood": "",
  "LDL receptors convert cholesterol to triglycerides, so their absence allows cholesterol to accumulate": "",
  "LDL receptors normally destroy cholesterol, so without them cholesterol builds up": "",
  "Non-functional LDL receptors prevent cells from taking up cholesterol-carrying LDL particles from the blood, causing cholesterol to remain in circulation and accumulate in arterial walls": "",
  "LDL receptors on cell surfaces bind LDL particles and mediate their endocytosis, removing cholesterol from the bloodstream. Without functional receptors, LDL cholesterol remains in the blood and deposits in arteries, leading to atherosclerosis.": "",
  "A botanist observes that desert plants have a thick waxy cuticle on their leaves. How does this lipid-based adaptation help the plants survive in arid conditions?": "",
  "The waxy coating attracts pollinators to the flowers": "",
  "The wax absorbs sunlight and converts it to chemical energy": "",
  "The wax stores water for the plant to use during drought": "",
  "The hydrophobic waxy cuticle reduces water loss through evaporation from the leaf surface": "",
  "Waxes are highly hydrophobic lipids that form waterproof barriers. The waxy cuticle on desert plant leaves minimizes transpirational water loss, which is critical for survival in environments with limited water availability.": "",
  "An endocrinologist explains to a patient that steroid hormones like cortisol can pass directly through cell membranes to bind intracellular receptors, unlike peptide hormones. What chemical property of steroids allows this?": "",
  "Steroids are nonpolar lipids derived from cholesterol, so they can dissolve through the hydrophobic core of the phospholipid bilayer": "",
  "Steroids carry a positive charge that repels the membrane's phosphate groups, creating a channel": "",
  "Steroids are small enough to pass through membrane pores": "",
  "Steroids are transported across the membrane by active transport pumps": "",
  "Steroid hormones are hydrophobic lipids derived from cholesterol. Their nonpolar nature allows them to pass directly through the hydrophobic interior of the phospholipid bilayer without the need for membrane transport proteins.": "",
  "A medical researcher studying obesity notes that a patient consuming excess carbohydrates (beyond immediate energy needs) still gains body fat even though they eat very little dietary fat. How is this possible biochemically?": "",
  "Excess carbohydrates attract water weight that appears as body fat": "",
  "Carbohydrates are converted to protein, which then becomes fat": "",
  "Excess carbohydrates are stored directly as cellulose in human fat cells": "",
  "The liver converts excess glucose into fatty acids through de novo lipogenesis, which are then assembled into triglycerides and stored in adipose tissue": "",
  "When carbohydrate intake exceeds energy demands and glycogen stores are full, the liver converts excess glucose into fatty acids through de novo lipogenesis. These fatty acids are esterified to glycerol to form triglycerides and stored in adipose tissue.": ""
